# Progress — Distributed Chat Application (in memory of Ventsislav)

## Architecture decisions log

| Decision | Choice | Notes |
|----------|--------|--------|
| Outbox / inbox storage | **Option A — In existing DB** | Outbox table and inbox (processed IDs) live in existing databases (e.g. outbox in Messages DB, inbox/processed_ids in Messages DB). No separate store for these tables. |
| Message history | HTTP GET, not WebSocket | Client fetches history via `GET /messages/:channelId`; API Gateway → Messaging Service → Messages DB. |
| Presence registration | Channel Service → Presence Service (HTTP) | Presence Service is sole owner of Presence Redis; Channel Service calls register/unregister/heartbeat. |
| Offline notifications | Notification Service resolves email via Auth Service | Messaging Service sends only `{ recipientId, issuer, messagePreview }`; Notification Service calls Auth Service for email. |
| Resilience (main) | Circuit breaker + retry with backoff/jitter | Circuit breaker on Messaging → Presence (fallback: assume offline). Retry + jitter on Messaging→Presence, Notification→Auth, Channel→Presence. |
| Resilience (bonus later) | Outbox + inbox | After project finish: outbox for at-least-once publish; inbox for idempotent consumption in worker. |
| Pub/sub (MVP) | Single global topic | One Redis Pub/Sub topic; payload includes `recipientIds`; Channel Services filter locally. Bonus: per-user/per-conversation topics later. |
| Persistent storage | Named Docker volumes | Users DB, Messages DB, Notification DB use named volumes; Presence Redis and Pub/Sub Redis are ephemeral. |
| Refresh token storage | **Separate table** | 1:N relationship (one user, many devices/sessions). Enables per-session revocation, token rotation, and reuse detection. |

