### Phase 3 — API Gateway

> **Flow:** Single entry point for all client traffic

- [ ] API Gateway service setup (NestJS or lightweight proxy)
- [ ] Route `/auth/*` → Auth Service
- [ ] JWT validation middleware on protected routes (verify Access Token, extract `userId`)
- [ ] Route `/messages/*` → Messaging Service
- [ ] Route `/channels/*` → Messaging Service
- [ ] Proxy `/ws` → Load Balancer (WebSocket upgrade)

### Phase 4 — WebSocket and Presence

> **Flow:** Client → API Gateway → Load Balancer → Channel Service → Presence Service → Presence Redis

- [ ] Load Balancer (e.g. Nginx): distribute WebSocket connections to Channel Services (no sticky sessions)
- [ ] Channel Service: WebSocket server; validate JWT on upgrade (`/ws?token=...`); associate connection with `userId`
- [ ] Presence Service: register, unregister, heartbeat (batched); sole owner of Presence Redis; TTL 30s
- [ ] Channel Service → Presence Service integration: on connect → `POST /presence/register`; on disconnect → `POST /presence/unregister`; heartbeat every 15s (batched)

### Phase 5 — Channels

> **Flow:** Client → API Gateway → Messaging Service → Channels DB

- [ ] Channels DB schema: `channels` table, `channel_members` table
- [ ] Create channel (DM or group): `POST /channels` with `{ type, name?, memberIds }`
- [ ] List user's channels: `GET /channels` → channels the authenticated user belongs to

### Phase 6 — Messaging (send and persist)

> **Flow:** Client (WS) → API Gateway → Load Balancer → Channel Service → Messaging Service → (parallel: Message Queue + Presence check) → (online: Pub/Sub → Channel Services → Client, offline: Notification Queue)

- [ ] Messaging Service: receive "send message" from Channel Service
- [ ] Write path: push to Message Queue (with retry)
- [ ] Messaging Processor Worker: consume Message Queue → write to Messages DB
- [ ] Presence check: call Presence Service (retry + circuit breaker; fallback: assume offline)
- [ ] Online delivery: publish to Redis Pub/Sub (`recipientIds`, message, issuer, sentAt, channelId)
- [ ] Offline delivery: push to Notification Queue (`recipientId`, issuer, messagePreview)
- [ ] Channel Services: subscribe to Pub/Sub; deliver to local connections matching `recipientIds`

### Phase 7 — Message History

> **Flow:** Client → API Gateway → Messaging Service → Messages DB

- [ ] `GET /messages/:channelId` → Messaging Service queries Messages DB (paginated)
- [ ] API Gateway routes history requests to Messaging Service
- [ ] Client: fetch history via HTTP when opening a conversation; real-time updates via WebSocket

### Phase 8 — Notifications

> **Flow:** Notification Queue → Notification Service → Auth Service (resolve email) → send email → Notification DB

- [ ] Notification Service: consume Notification Queue
- [ ] Resolve recipient email: call Auth Service (`GET /users/:id/email` or similar)
- [ ] Send email notification (e.g. SMTP / third-party provider)
- [ ] Write notification record to Notification DB

### Phase 9 — Resilience (main)

- [ ] Retry with exponential backoff + jitter on: Messaging→Presence, Notification→Auth, Channel→Presence
- [ ] Circuit breaker on Messaging→Presence; fallback: assume offline, push to Notification Queue

### Phase 10 — Polish and bonus (later)

- [ ] Friends/contacts (if in scope): Users DB + `GET /users/friends`; Gateway route
- [ ] **(Bonus)** Outbox pattern: Messaging Service writes to outbox table in Messages DB; Outbox Publisher polls → Message Queue + Pub/Sub
- [ ] **(Bonus)** Inbox pattern: Messaging Processor Worker tracks processed message IDs; idempotent consumption

